---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Wrapper from "@/components/fundations/containers/Wrapper.astro";
import Text from "@/components/fundations/elements/Text.astro";
const content = [
  {
    label: "Author",
    text: `This essay was written by <a href="https://michaelandreuzza.com/" class="underline hover:no-underline">Michael Andreuzza</a> at <a href="https://lexingtonthemes.com/" class="underline hover:no-underline">Lexington Themes</a>, the individual responsible for making this argument possible during a rare moment of unallocated time.`,
  },
  {
    label: "Summary",
    text: `<strong>Most websites are content with a small amount of interactivity.</strong> If you are shipping a full single-page application for a marketing site, you are not “modern.” You are being architecturally negligent, prioritizing developer convenience over user experience, and actively degrading the quality of the web.`,
  },
  {
    label: "What is this?",
    text: `This is a public service announcement for developers who are still building websites as if the last decade of tooling evolution never happened, and proudly presenting the result as innovation.`,
  },
  {
    label: "Two misguided belief systems",
    items: [
      `<strong>"No frameworks ever."</strong> Congratulations: you have rebuilt a significantly worse CMS with inferior routing, brittle builds, and no meaningful guardrails. Your system is one junior developer away from becoming an unmaintainable collection of markup.`,
      `<strong>"SPA for everything."</strong> Congratulations: you shipped hundreds of kilobytes of JavaScript to render static content. Your users did not consent to executing your architectural thesis in their browser.`,
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "Astro exists because",
    items: [
      "Pages",
      "Content",
      "Navigation",
      "Forms",
      "A small number of interactive widgets",
    ],
    suffix:
      "not because websites should masquerade as desktop applications awkwardly embedded in browser tabs.",
  },
  {
    label: "Why Astro instead of “Pure HTML” idealism?",
    text: `Because “pure HTML at scale” is a comforting myth that collapses the moment your site grows beyond a trivial number of pages and shared concerns.`,
  },
  {
    label: "What inevitably goes wrong",
    items: [
      "Layouts are duplicated endlessly instead of abstracted",
      "A “small amount of JavaScript” devolves into an unstructured tangle",
      "Content becomes loosely defined and error-prone",
      "The build process turns into a fragile chain of scripts and workarounds",
    ],
    suffix: `Astro provides structure without forcing everything into the client or demanding ideological purity.`,
  },
  {
    label: "What you gain",
    items: [
      "Componentization without committing to a monolithic JavaScript framework",
      "Proper layouts instead of copy-paste repetition",
      "Predictable file-based routing",
      "Typed content collections that prevent broken frontmatter",
      "The freedom to use React, Vue, or Svelte only where it is justified",
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "December 2025",
    text: `And yes, this remains true in December 2025: <strong>Astro ships zero client-side JavaScript by default.</strong> No caveats. No hidden costs. No unnecessary hydration.`,
  },
  {
    label: "Why Astro instead of defaulting to React for everything?",
    text: `Because React is excellent, <strong>for applications.</strong><br><br>Most websites are not applications, regardless of how strongly some teams wish they were.`,
  },
  {
    label: "If your site consists of",
    items: [
      "Marketing pages",
      "Documentation",
      "A blog",
      "Landing pages",
      "An ecommerce frontend (not a client-side simulation)",
    ],
    suffix: `then shipping a full SPA is equivalent to deploying industrial machinery to solve a trivial problem.`,
  },
  {
    label: "Philosophy",
    text: `Astro embodies the “HTML-first, JavaScript-when-necessary” approach that many developers claim to follow but rarely enforce.`,
  },
  {
    label: "Islands: often acknowledged, frequently misapplied",
    text: `Here is the correct mental model.<br><br><strong>Your page is static by default. Interactivity is the exception.</strong><br><br>Need a carousel? Make it an island.<br>Pricing toggle? Island.<br>Search? Island.<br><br>Everything else remains server-rendered, predictable, fast, and respectful of the user.`,
  },
  {
    label: "This results in",
    items: [
      "Substantially less JavaScript delivered to users",
      "Fewer hydration-related failures",
      "Reduced debugging complexity",
      "Pages that function immediately rather than after a JavaScript initialization phase",
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "Rule",
    text: `You do not need to hydrate the entire page. You need to hydrate the single component that requires it, and leave the rest alone.`,
  },
  {
    label: "The framework reality check",
    text: "Use Astro when:",
    items: [
      "Your site is primarily content with selective interactivity",
      "SEO is a real requirement, not a slide-deck bullet point",
      "You want componentization without an SPA performance penalty",
      "Frameworks are tools, not defaults",
      "Interactivity is localized rather than global",
      "You want maintainability beyond a few dozen pages",
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "Note",
    text: `If your response is “I can do this with vanilla JavaScript,” that may be true, but difficulty alone is not a virtue, and unnecessary friction is not a mark of expertise.`,
  },
  {
    label: "When you should not use Astro",
    text: "Astro is not appropriate for:",
    items: [
      "Heavy client-side applications with pervasive shared state",
      "Real-time collaborative systems",
      "Interfaces where nearly every element is interactive",
      "Complex offline-first applications",
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "If your UI behaves like a continuously running program",
    text: "Stop treating it as a website and use:",
    items: [
      "React / Next",
      "SvelteKit",
      "Remix",
      "Whatever your team can competently maintain",
    ],
    suffix:
      "Astro is designed for websites that behave like websites, with selective application-level behavior where appropriate.",
  },
  {
    label: "“What about bloat?”",
    text: `When used correctly, Astro <strong>does not ship what you do not use</strong>. That is the design goal.<br><br>If your Astro site delivers hundreds of kilobytes of JavaScript, you have ignored the model and reconstructed an SPA. That outcome reflects misuse, not a tooling flaw.`,
  },
  {
    label: "The real issue is not Astro vs React",
    text: `The real issue is the inability to evaluate the problem at hand. Tool choice is treated as identity rather than engineering judgment.<br><br>Some teams build everything as if it were static marketing collateral.<br>Others build everything as if it were a state-saturated application.`,
  },
  {
    label: "Choose based on reality",
    text: "Not preference or ideology:",
    items: [
      "Website? <strong>Astro.</strong>",
      "Application? <strong>Full framework.</strong>",
      "Hybrid? <strong>Astro with islands.</strong>",
    ],
  },
  {
    label: "Advice",
    text: `Stop treating tools as extensions of personal identity. This is engineering. Approach it with professionalism.`,
  },
];
const inspirations = [
  {
    url: "https://motherfuckingwebsite.com/",
    name: "motherfuckingwebsite.com",
    desc: "the original provocation",
  },
  {
    url: "https://justfuckinguse.com/",
    name: "justfuckinguse.com",
    desc: "the collected arguments",
  },
  {
